1 On a showing of good cause, the State Board of Education may waive the requirement that
2 the opening date for students be no earlier than the Monday closest to August 26 and may allow
3 the local board of education to set an opening date no earlier than the Monday closest to August
4 19, to the extent that school calendars are able to provide sufficient days to accommodate
5 anticipated makeup days due to school closings. A local board may revise the scheduled closing
6 date if necessary in order to comply with the minimum requirements for instructional days or
7 instructional time. For purposes of this subsection, the term "good cause" means that schools in
8 any local school administrative unit in a county have been closed eight days per year during any
9 four of the last 10 years because of severe weather conditions, energy shortages, power failures,
10 or other emergency situations.
11 (d2) Modified Calendars and Year-Round Schools. – The required opening and closing
12 dates under this subsection section shall not apply to (i) any school that a local board designated
13 as having a modified calendar for the 2003-2004 school year or to any school that was part of a
14 planned program in the 2003-2004 school year for a system of modified calendar schools, so long
15 as the school operates under a modified calendar.calendar and (ii) year-round schools.
16 …
17 (f) Definitions. – The following definitions shall apply in this section:
18 (1) Reserved.
19 (2) Reserved.
20 (3) Good cause. – The closure of schools in any local school administrative unit
21 in a county for eight days per year during any four of the last 10 years because
22 of severe weather conditions, energy shortages, power failures, or other
23 emergency situations.
24 …."
25 SECTION 2. Part 2 of Article 8 of Chapter 115C of the General Statutes is amended
26 by adding the following new sections to read:
27 "§ 115C-84.2A. School calendar enforcement; withholding of funds.
28 (a) The State Board of Education shall ensure that local boards of education comply with
29 G.S. 115C-84.2.
30 (b) The Superintendent of Public Instruction shall notify the State Board of Education
31 and shall investigate whether the local board of education is in compliance with G.S. 115C-84.2
32 if the Superintendent receives information from any of the following indicating that a local board
33 of education has not complied with G.S. 115C-84.2:
34 (1) A report to the Department of Public Instruction, Superintendent of Public
35 Instruction, or State Board of Education.
36 (2) A report by an employee of the Department of Public Instruction responsible
37 for monitoring compliance of a local school administrative unit.
38 (3) Any other source the Superintendent deems credible.
39 (c) The Superintendent shall report the findings of the investigation to the State Board of
40 Education within 60 days of the receipt of the information under subsection (b) of this section.
41 The State Board shall schedule consideration of the report no later than the next regular meeting
42 occurring more than five days after submission of the report.
43 (d) Following submission of the report by the Superintendent, if the State Board of
44 Education by a majority vote finds that the local board of education has not complied with
45 G.S. 115C-84.2, the State Board shall direct the local board of education to take action to remedy
46 the violation and submit documentation of the remedy to the State Board within 60 days. The
47 State Board shall find that a local board of education is noncompliant with G.S. 115C-84.2 if the
48 Superintendent's report indicates any of the following have occurred:
49 (1) The local board of education adopted a resolution or policy stating that the
50 local school administrative unit will not comply with G.S. 115C-84.2.
Page 2 Senate Bill 754-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) The local board of education approved any action counter to or incompatible
2 with compliance with G.S. 115C-84.2.
3 (e) If the local board of education fails to comply with the State Board of Education
4 direction as provided in subsection (d) of this section, the State Board shall withhold the local
5 school administrative unit's central office administration allotment until the State Board
6 determines the local board is no longer noncompliant.
7 (f) If the State Board of Education takes action under subsection (e) of this section, the
8 State Board shall report this action to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee,
9 within 60 days of the action. The General Assembly shall consider, no later than the next session
10 of the General Assembly, the future governance of the identified local school administrative unit.
11 "§ 115C-84.2B. School calendar enforcement; liability of local board.
12 (a) A person that resides or maintains a place of business within the boundaries of a local
13 school administrative unit may bring an action against the local board of education if the board
14 has not complied with G.S. 115C-84.2. For purpose of this section, "person" means any natural
15 person or corporation, nonprofit corporation, limited liability company, trust, association,
16 partnership, joint venture, subsidiary, or other business entity.
17 (b) For any action brought pursuant to this section, if the court finds that a local board of
18 education has not complied with G.S. 115C-84.2, the court shall issue a declaratory judgment
19 that the board is noncompliant, provide injunctive relief, and award a prevailing claimant
20 reasonable attorneys' fees and costs. The court may impose a civil penalty against the board of
21 up to ten thousand dollars ($10,000)."
22 SECTION 3. This act is effective when it becomes law and applies beginning with
23 the 2026-2027 school year.
